# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: epidemiology-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] A **case–control study** (also known as **case–referent study**) is a type of observational study in which two existing groups differing in outcome are identified and compared on the basis of some supposed causal attribute.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Case–control studies are often used to identify factors that may contribute to a medical condition by comparing subjects who have the condition with patients who do not have the condition but are otherwise similar.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] They require fewer resources but provide less evidence for causal inference than a randomized controlled trial.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] A case–control study is often used to produce an odds ratio.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Some statistical methods make it possible to use a case–control study to also estimate relative risk, risk differences, and other quantities.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Porta's *Dictionary of Epidemiology* defines the case–control study as: "an observational epidemiological study of persons with the disease (or another outcome variable) of interest and a suitable control group of persons without the disease (comparison group, reference group).
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The case–control study is frequently contrasted with cohort studies, wherein exposed and unexposed subjects are observed until they develop an outcome of interest.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Controls need not be in good health; inclusion of sick people is sometimes appropriate, as the control group should represent those at risk of becoming a case.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Controls should come from the same population as the cases, and their selection should be independent of the exposures of interest.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Controls can carry the same disease as the experimental group, but of another grade/severity, therefore being different from the outcome of interest.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] However, because the difference between the cases and the controls will be smaller, this results in a lower power to detect an exposure effect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] As with any epidemiological study, greater numbers in the study will increase the power of the study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Numbers of cases and controls do not have to be equal.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] In many situations, it is much easier to recruit controls than to find cases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Increasing the number of controls above the number of cases, up to a ratio of about 4 to 1, may be a cost-effective way to improve the study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] A prospective study watches for outcomes, such as the development of a disease, during the study period and relates this to other factors such as suspected risk or protection factor(s).
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The study usually involves taking a cohort of subjects and watching them over a long period.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The outcome of interest should be common; otherwise, the number of outcomes observed will be too small to be statistically meaningful (indistinguishable from those that may have arisen by chance).
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] All efforts should be made to avoid sources of bias such as the loss of individuals to follow up during the study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Prospective studies usually have fewer potential sources of bias and confounding than retrospective studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] A retrospective study, on the other hand, looks backwards and examines exposures to suspected risk or protection factors in relation to an outcome that is established at the start of the study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Many valuable case–control studies, such as Lane and Claypon's 1926 investigation of risk factors for breast cancer, were retrospective investigations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Most sources of error due to confounding and bias are more common in retrospective studies than in prospective studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] For this reason, retrospective investigations are often criticised.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] If the outcome of interest is uncommon, however, the size of prospective investigation required to estimate relative risk is often too large to be feasible.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] In retrospective studies the odds ratio provides an estimate of relative risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] One should take special care to avoid sources of bias and confounding in retrospective studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Case–control studies are a relatively inexpensive and frequently used type of epidemiological study that can be carried out by small teams or individual researchers in single facilities in a way that more structured experimental studies often cannot be.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] They have pointed the way to a number of important discoveries and advances.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The case–control study design is often used in the study of rare diseases or as a preliminary study where little is known about the association between the risk factor and disease of interest.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Compared to prospective cohort studies they tend to be less costly and shorter in duration.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] In several situations, they have greater statistical power than cohort studies, which must often wait for a 'sufficient' number of disease events to accrue.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Case–control studies are observational in nature and thus do not provide the same level of evidence as randomized controlled trials.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The results may be confounded by other factors, to the extent of giving the opposite answer to better studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] A meta-analysis of what was considered 30 high-quality studies concluded that use of a product halved a risk, when in fact the risk was, if anything, increased.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] It may also be more difficult to establish the timeline of exposure to disease outcome in the setting of a case–control study than within a prospective cohort study design where the exposure is ascertained prior to following the subjects over time in order to ascertain their outcome status.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The most important drawback in case–control studies relates to the difficulty of obtaining reliable information about an individual's exposure status over time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Case–control studies are therefore placed low in the hierarchy of evidence.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] One of the most significant triumphs of the case–control study was the demonstration of the link between tobacco smoking and lung cancer, by Richard Doll and Bradford Hill.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] They showed a statistically significant association in a large case–control study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Opponents argued for many years that this type of study cannot prove causation, but the eventual results of cohort studies confirmed the causal link which the case–control studies suggested, and it is now accepted that tobacco smoking is the cause of about 87% of all lung cancer mortality in the US.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Case–control studies were initially analyzed by testing whether or not there were significant differences between the proportion of exposed subjects among cases and controls.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] Subsequently, Cornfield pointed out that, when the disease outcome of interest is rare, the odds ratio of exposure can be used to estimate the relative risk (see rare disease assumption).
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The validity of the odds ratio depends highly on the nature of the disease studied, on the sampling methodology and on the type of follow-up.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] When the logistic regression model is used to model the case–control data and the odds ratio is of interest, both the prospective and retrospective likelihood methods will lead to identical maximum likelihood estimations for covariate, except for the intercept.
[src:epidemiology-methods/case-control-study] The usual methods of estimating more interpretable parameters than odds ratios—such as risk ratios, levels, and differences—is biased if applied to case–control data, but special statistical procedures provide easy to use consistent estimators.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] A **cohort study** is a particular form of longitudinal study that samples a cohort (a group of people who share a defining characteristic, typically those who experienced a common event in a selected period, such as birth or graduation), performing a cross-section at intervals through time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] It is a type of panel study where the individuals in the panel share a common characteristic.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Cohort studies represent one of the fundamental designs of epidemiology which are used in research in the fields of medicine, pharmacy, nursing, psychology, social science, and in any field reliant on 'difficult to reach' answers that are based on evidence (statistics).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Cohort studies differ from clinical trials in that no intervention, treatment, or exposure is administered to participants in a cohort design; and no control group is defined.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Rather, cohort studies are largely about the life histories of segments of populations and the individual people who constitute these segments.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Exposures or protective factors are identified as preexisting characteristics of participants.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The study is controlled by including other common characteristics of the cohort in the statistical analysis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Both exposure/treatment and control variables are measured at baseline.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Participants are then followed over time to observe the incidence rate of the disease or outcome in question.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Regression analysis can then be used to evaluate the extent to which the exposure or treatment variable contributes to the incidence of the disease, while accounting for other variables that may be at play.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] This minimizes the chance that results will be influenced by confounding variables, particularly ones that are unknown.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] However, educated hypotheses based on prior research and background knowledge are used to select variables to be included in the regression model for cohort studies, and statistical methods can be used to identify and account for potential confounders from these variables.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Bias can also be mitigated in a cohort study when selecting participants for the cohort.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] RCTs may not be suitable in all cases; such as when the outcome is a negative health effect and the exposure is hypothesized to be a risk factor for the outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Ethical standards, and morality, would prevent the use of risk factors in RCTs.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The natural or incidental exposure to these risk factors (e.g. time spent in the sun), or self-administered exposure (e.g. smoking), can be measured without subjecting participants to risk factors outside of their individual lifestyles, habits, and choices.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Cohort studies can be retrospective (looking back in time, thus using existing data such as medical records or claims database) or prospective (requiring the collection of new data).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Retrospective cohort studies restrict the investigators' ability to reduce confounding and bias because collected information is restricted to data that already exists.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] There are advantages to this design, however, as retrospective studies are much cheaper and faster because the data has already been collected and stored.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] A cohort is a group of people who share a common characteristic or experience within a defined period (e.g., are currently living, are exposed to a drug or vaccine or pollutant, or undergo a certain medical procedure).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Thus a group of people who were born on a day or in a particular period, say 1948, form a birth cohort.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The comparison group may be the general population from which the cohort is drawn, or it may be another cohort of persons thought to have had little or no exposure to the substance under investigation, but otherwise similar.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Alternatively, subgroups within the cohort may be compared with each other.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] In medicine, a cohort study is often undertaken to obtain evidence to try to refute the existence of a suspected association between cause and effect; failure to refute a hypothesis often strengthens confidence in it.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Crucially, the cohort is identified before the appearance of the disease under investigation.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The study groups follow a group of people who do not have the disease for a period of time and see who develops the disease (new incidence).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The cohort cannot therefore be defined as a group of people who already have the disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Prospective (longitudinal) cohort studies between exposure and disease strongly aid in studying causal associations, though distinguishing true causality usually requires further corroboration from further experimental trials.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The advantage of prospective cohort study data is that it can help determine risk factors for contracting a new disease because it is a longitudinal observation of the individual through time, and the collection of data at regular intervals, so recall error is reduced.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] However, cohort studies are expensive to conduct, are sensitive to attrition and take a long follow-up time to generate useful data.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Nevertheless, the results that are obtained from long-term cohort studies are of substantially superior quality to those obtained from retrospective/cross-sectional studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Prospective cohort studies are considered to yield the most reliable results in observational epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] They enable a wide range of exposure-disease associations to be studied.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Some cohort studies track groups of children from their birth, and record a wide range of information (exposures) about them.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The value of a cohort study depends on the researchers' capacity to stay in touch with all members of the cohort.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Some studies have continued for decades.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] In a cohort study, the population under investigation consists of individuals who are at risk of developing a specific disease or health outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] An example of an epidemiological question that can be answered using a cohort study is whether exposure to X (say, smoking) associates with outcome Y (say, lung cancer).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] For example, in 1951, the British Doctors Study was started.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Using a cohort which included both smokers (the exposed group) and non-smokers (the unexposed group).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] By 1956, the study provided convincing proof of the association between smoking and the incidence of lung cancer.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] In a cohort study, the groups are *matched* in terms of many other variables such as economic status and other health status so that the variable being assessed, the independent variable (in this case, smoking) can be isolated as the cause of the dependent variable (in this case, lung cancer).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] In this example, a statistically significant increase in the incidence of lung cancer in the smoking group as compared to the non-smoking group is evidence in favor of the hypothesis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] However, rare outcomes, such as lung cancer, are generally not studied with the use of a cohort study, but are rather studied with the use of a case-control study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] In the Arts, Cohort Succession can explain most change in literature, art, intellectualism, political opinions, and phonology.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Shorter term studies are commonly used in medical research as a form of clinical trial, or means to test a particular hypothesis of clinical importance.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Such studies typically follow two groups of patients for a period of time and compare an endpoint or outcome measure between the two groups.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Randomized controlled trials, or RCTs, are a superior methodology in the hierarchy of evidence, because they limit the potential for bias by randomly assigning one patient pool to an intervention and another patient pool to non-intervention (or placebo).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] This minimizes the chance that the incidence of confounding variables will differ between the two groups.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Nevertheless, it is sometimes not practical or ethical to perform RCTs to answer a clinical question.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] To take our example, if we already had reasonable evidence that smoking causes lung cancer then persuading a pool of non-smokers to take up smoking in order to test this hypothesis would generally be considered unethical.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Two examples of cohort studies that have been going on for more than 50 years are the Framingham Heart Study and the National Child Development Study (NCDS), the most widely researched of the British birth cohort studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Key findings of NCDS and a detailed profile of the study appear in the *International Journal of Epidemiology*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The Dunedin Multidisciplinary Health and Development Study has been studying the thousand people born in Dunedin, New Zealand, in 1972–1973.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The subjects are interviewed regularly, with Phase (age) 52 starting in 2024.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The largest cohort study in women is the Nurses' Health Study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Starting in 1976, it is tracking over 120,000 nurses and has been analyzed for many different conditions and outcomes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The largest cohort study in Africa is the Birth to Twenty Study, which began in 1990 and tracks a cohort of over 3,000 children born in the weeks following Nelson Mandela's release from prison.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Other famous examples are the Grant Study tracking a number of Harvard graduates from ca.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] 1950.77, the Whitehall Study tracking 10,308 British civil servants, and the Caerphilly Heart Disease Study, which since 1979 has studied a representative sample of 2,512 men, drawn from the Welsh town of Caerphilly.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The ASPREE-XT study is designed to determine whether there are long-lasting effects of an average of four–five years of treatment with daily low-dose aspirin, with outcome measures including cancer mortality.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] As of September 2018, there were 16,703 ASPREE-XT participants in Australia.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] It has been proposed that the existing ASPREE-XT study could provide a platform for a future multigenerational research study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The diagram indicates the starting point and direction of cohort and case-control studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] In case-control studies the analysis proceeds from documented disease and investigations are made to arrive at the possible causes of the disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] A current cohort study represents a true prospective study where the data concerning exposure are assembled prior to the occurrence of the fact to be studied, for instance a disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] An example of a current cohort study is the Oxford Family Planning Association Study in the United Kingdom, which aimed to provide a balanced view of the beneficial and harmful effects of different methods of contraception.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] This study has provided a large amount of information on the efficacy and safety of contraceptive methods, and in particular oral contraceptives (OCs), diaphragms and intrauterine device (IUDs).
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] A "prospective cohort" defines the groups before the study is done, while historical studies, which are sometimes referred to as "retrospective cohort", define the grouping after the data is collected.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Examples of a retrospective cohort are *Long-Term Mortality after Gastric Bypass Surgery* and *The Lothian Birth Cohort Studies*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Although historical studies are sometimes referred to as retrospective study, it a misnomer as the methodological principles of historical cohort studies and prospective studies are the same.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] A nested case-control study is a case control nested inside of a cohort study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The procedure begins like a normal cohort study, however, as participants develop the outcome of interest they are selected as cases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Once the cases are identified, controls are selected and matched to each case.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] The process for selecting and matching cases is identical to a normal case control study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] An example of a nested case-control study is *Inflammatory markers and the risk of coronary heart disease in men and women*, which was a case control analyses extracted from the Framingham Heart Study cohort.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Nested case-controls have the advantage of reducing the number of participants that require details follow up or diagnostic testing to assess outcome or exposure status.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] However, this will also reduce the power of the study, when compared to larger cohort the study population is drawn from.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Panel surveys are another important sub-type of longitudinal study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] They differ from cohort studies by starting with representative cross-sectional samples, rather than cohorts defined by an event.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Household panels draw representative samples of households and survey them, following all individuals through time on a usual annual basis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] For an example in business analysis, see cohort analysis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Conventionally, cohort studies require manual definitions of the common characteristics, which are time-consuming and labor-intensive, demanding extensive domain expertise.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] To address these limitations, researchers have increasingly explored the integration of AI technologies (e.g., CohortNet.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] COOL) to automate the identification of cohorts with their definitions.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] For example, in healthcare, we can identify patients with a certain combination of feature conditions as a specific cohort, typically resulting in a similar outcome or end-point.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] Once the cohort is identified, we further learn the commonalities among the associated patients and obtain meaningful cohort representations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/cohort-study] These AI-derived cohorts not only enhance the ability to evaluate new patients but also hold significant potential to accelerate medical research and discovery.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In causal inference, **confounding** is a form of systematic error (or bias) that can distort estimates of causal effects in observational studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A **confounder** is traditionally understood to be a variable that (1) independently predicts the outcome (or dependent variable), (2) is associated with the exposure (or independent variable), and (3) is not on the causal pathway between the exposure and the outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Failure to control for a confounder results in a spurious association between exposure and outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Confounding is a causal concept rather than a purely statistical one, and therefore cannot be fully described by correlations or associations alone.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The presence of confounders helps explain why correlation does not imply causation, and why careful study design and analytical methods (such as randomization, statistical adjustment, or causal diagrams) are required to distinguish causal effects from spurious associations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Several notation systems and formal frameworks, such as causal directed acyclic graphs (DAGs), have been developed to represent and detect confounding, making it possible to identify when a variable must be controlled for in order to obtain an unbiased estimate of a causal effect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Confounders are threats to internal validity.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Confounding is defined in terms of the data generating model.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Let *X* be an exposure (or independent variable), and let *Y* be the outcome (or dependent variable).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Traditionally, a variable *Z* was considered to confound the relationship between *X* and *Y* if *Z* (1) independently predicts *Y*, (2) is associated with *X*, and (3) is not on the causal pathway between *X* and *Y*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Not controlling for *Z* introduces a spurious relationship between *X* and *Y*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] However, several developments in causal inference over the past decades have shown that this definition of confounding is inadequate.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] This is because there can be pre-exposure variables associated with the outcome that, when controlled for, introduce rather than eliminate bias.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Modern causal inference therefore typically defines a confounder in terms of the *minimally sufficient adjustment set*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Formally, a set of variables *Z* is a *sufficient adjustment set* for the effect of *X* on *Y* if, conditional on *Z*, the potential outcomes are independent of *X*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] I.e. after adjusting for *Z*, the exposed and unexposed groups are exchangeable with respect to the outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A *minimally sufficient adjustment set* is an adjustment set *Z* where every member of *Z* is required to control for confounding.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Under this framework, a confounder is defined as a member of the minimally sufficient adjustment set.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In the language of directed acyclic graphs, confounding corresponds to the presence of one or more open backdoor paths between *X* and *Y*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A set of variables *Z* is a sufficient adjustment set if conditioning on *Z* blocks all backdoor paths from *X* to *Y*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The set is minimally sufficient if no proper subset of *Z* satisfies this property.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Removing any variable from a minimally sufficient set reopens at least one backdoor path.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A trucking company compares the fuel economy of trucks from two manufacturers (“A” and “B”) by measuring miles per gallon over one month.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] They find that A trucks appear more fuel-efficient.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] However, A trucks are more often assigned highway routes while B trucks are more often assigned city routes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Here, truck make is the independent variable, MPG is the dependent variable, and route type (or proportion of city driving) is the confounder.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Because route type affects MPG and the route type differs across truck make, it confounds the comparison.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Thus the observed difference likely reflects highway vs. city driving rather than truck make.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A scientist is studying the relationship between birth order (1st child, 2nd child, etc.) and the presence of Down syndrome in the child.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In this scenario, maternal age is a confounding variable, as it influences both the independent variable (birth order), and the dependent variable (Down syndrome).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A scientist is studying the relationship between smoking status (smoker vs. non-smoker) and the presence of lung disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Alcohol consumption and diet affect health regardless of smoking status (a smoker and non-smoker with similar alcohol use and diet may have similar health risks).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Alcohol consumption and diet are associated with smoking status (smokers are, on average, more likely to drink alcohol or have less healthy diets than non-smokers).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Alcohol consumption and diet are not consequences of smoking itself (smoking does not necessarily cause higher alcohol intake or poor diet, even if they are correlated).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In this scenario, alcohol consumption or diet is a confounding variable, because it influences both the independent variable (smoking status) and the dependent variable (health outcome).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] If these factors are not controlled, the observed association between smoking and lung disease may be partly or entirely due to differences in alcohol use or diet rather than smoking itself.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Consider a researcher attempting to assess the effectiveness of drug *X*, from population data in which drug usage was a patient's choice.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The data shows that gender (*Z*) influences a patient's choice of drug as well as their chances of recovery (*Y*).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] because the observational quantity contains information about the correlation between *X* and *Z*, and the interventional quantity does not (since *X* is not correlated with *Z* in a randomized experiment).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] It can be shown that, in cases where only observational data is available, an unbiased estimate of the desired quantity $P(y\mid {\text{do}}(x))$ , can be obtained by "adjusting" for all confounding factors, namely, conditioning on their various values and averaging the result.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] which gives an unbiased estimate for the causal effect of *X* on *Y*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The same adjustment formula works when there are multiple confounders except, in this case, the choice of a set *Z* of variables that would guarantee unbiased estimates must be done with caution.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The criterion for a proper choice of variables is called the Back-Door and requires that the chosen set *Z* "blocks" (or intercepts) every path between *X* and *Y* that contains an arrow into X.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Such sets are called "Back-Door admissible" and may include variables which are not common causes of *X* and *Y*, but merely proxies thereof.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In this way the physician can predict the likely effect of administering the drug from observational studies in which the conditional probabilities appearing on the right-hand side of the equation can be estimated by regression.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Contrary to common beliefs, adding covariates to the adjustment set *Z* can introduce bias.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In general, confounding can be controlled by adjustment if and only if there is a set of observed covariates that satisfies the Back-Door condition.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Moreover, if *Z* is such a set, then the adjustment formula of Eq.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Pearl's do-calculus provides all possible conditions under which $P(y\mid {\text{do}}(x))$ can be estimated, not necessarily by adjustment.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Greenland, Robins and Pearl note an early use of the term "confounding" in causal inference by John Stuart Mill in 1843.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Fisher introduced the word "confounding" in his 1935 book "The Design of Experiments" to refer specifically to a consequence of blocking (i.e., partitioning) the set of treatment combinations in a factorial experiment, whereby certain interactions may be "confounded with blocks".
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] This popularized the notion of confounding in statistics, although Fisher was concerned with the control of heterogeneity in experimental units, not with causal inference.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] According to Vandenbroucke (2004) it was Kish who used the word "confounding" in the sense of "incomparability" of two or more groups (e.g., exposed and unexposed) in an observational study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Formal conditions defining what makes certain groups "comparable" and others "incomparable" were later developed in epidemiology by Greenland and Robins (1986) using the counterfactual language of Neyman (1935) and Rubin (1974).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] These were later supplemented by graphical criteria such as the Back-Door condition (Pearl 1993; Greenland, Robins and Pearl 1999).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Graphical criteria were shown to be formally equivalent to the counterfactual definition but more transparent to researchers relying on process models.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In the case of risk assessments evaluating the magnitude and nature of risk to human health, it is important to control for confounding to isolate the effect of a particular hazard such as a food additive, pesticide, or new drug.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] For prospective studies, it is difficult to recruit and screen for volunteers with the same background (age, diet, education, geography, etc.), and in historical studies, there can be similar variability.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Due to the inability to control for variability of volunteers and human studies, confounding is a particular challenge.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] For these reasons, experiments offer a way to avoid most forms of confounding.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In some disciplines, confounding is categorized into different types.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In epidemiology, one type is "confounding by indication", which relates to confounding from observational studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Because prognostic factors may influence treatment decisions (and bias estimates of treatment effects), controlling for known prognostic factors may reduce this problem, but it is always possible that a forgotten or unknown factor was not included or that factors interact complexly.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Confounding by indication has been described as the most important limitation of observational studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Randomized trials are not affected by confounding by indication due to random assignment.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Confounding variables may also be categorised according to their source.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The choice of measurement instrument (operational confound), situational characteristics (procedural confound), or inter-individual differences (person confound).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] A reduction in the potential for the occurrence and effect of confounding factors can be obtained by increasing the types and numbers of comparisons performed in an analysis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] If measures or manipulations of core constructs are confounded (i.e. operational or procedural confounds exist), subgroup analysis may not reveal problems in the analysis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Additionally, increasing the number of comparisons can create other problems (see multiple comparisons).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Peer review is a process that can assist in reducing instances of confounding, either before study implementation or after analysis has occurred.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Peer review relies on collective expertise within a discipline to identify potential weaknesses in study design and analysis, including ways in which results may depend on confounding.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Similarly, replication can test for the robustness of findings from one study under alternative study conditions or alternative analyses (e.g., controlling for potential confounds not identified in the initial study).
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Confounding effects may be less likely to occur and act similarly at multiple times and locations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In selecting study sites, the environment can be characterized in detail at the study sites to ensure sites are ecologically similar and therefore less likely to have confounding variables.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Lastly, the relationship between the environmental variables that possibly confound the analysis and the measured parameters can be studied.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The information pertaining to environmental variables can then be used in site-specific models to identify residual variance that may be due to real effects.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Ethical considerations: In double-blind and randomized controlled trials, participants are not aware that they are recipients of sham treatments and may be denied effective treatments.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] There is a possibility that patients only agree to invasive surgery (which carry real medical risks) under the understanding that they are receiving treatment.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Although this is an ethical concern, it is not a complete account of the situation.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] For surgeries that are currently being performed regularly, but for which there is no concrete evidence of a genuine effect, there may be ethical issues to continue such surgeries.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] In such circumstances, many of people are exposed to the real risks of surgery yet these treatments may possibly offer no discernible benefit.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Sham-surgery control is a method that may allow medical science to determine whether a surgical procedure is efficacious or not.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Given that there are known risks associated with medical operations, it is questionably ethical to allow unverified surgeries to be conducted ad infinitum into the future.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Concerns have been raised that confounding in medical research can product false null results due to decreasing exposure reliability and increasing sibling-correlations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Artifacts are variables that should have been systematically varied, either within or across studies, but that were accidentally held constant.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Artifacts are thus threats to external validity.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Artifacts are factors that covary with the treatment and the outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Campbell and Stanley identify several artifacts.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] The major threats to internal validity are history, maturation, testing, instrumentation, statistical regression, selection, experimental mortality, and selection-history interactions.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] One way to minimize the influence of artifacts is to use a pretest-posttest control group design.
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Within this design, "groups of people who are initially equivalent (at the pretest phase) are randomly assigned to receive the experimental treatment or a control condition and then assessed again after this differential experience (posttest phase)".
[src:epidemiology-methods/confounding] Thus, any effects of artifacts are (ideally) equally distributed in participants in both the treatment and control conditions.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] It is a cornerstone of public health, and shapes policy decisions and evidence-based practice by identifying risk factors for disease and targets for preventive healthcare.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiologists help with study design, collection, and statistical analysis of data, amend interpretation and dissemination of results (including peer review and occasional systematic review).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiology has helped develop methodology used in clinical research, public health studies, and, to a lesser extent, basic research in the biological sciences.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Major areas of epidemiological study include disease causation, transmission, outbreak investigation, disease surveillance, environmental epidemiology, forensic epidemiology, occupational epidemiology, screening, biomonitoring, and comparisons of treatment effects such as in clinical trials.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiologists rely on other scientific disciplines like biology to better understand disease processes, statistics to make efficient use of the data and draw appropriate conclusions, social sciences to better understand proximate and distal causes, and engineering for exposure assessment.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiology, literally meaning 'the study of what is upon the people', is derived from Greek *epi* 'upon, among'; *demos* 'people' and *logos* 'study', referring to the study of human populations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, the term is widely used in studies of zoological populations (veterinary epidemiology), although the term 'epizootiology' was historically used.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] 'Epidemiology' has also been applied to studies of plant populations (botanical or plant disease epidemiology).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The distinction between "epidemic" and "endemic" was first drawn by Hippocrates, The term "epidemiology" appears to have first been used to describe the study of epidemics in 1802 by the Spanish physician Joaquín de Villalba in *Epidemiología Española*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiologists also study the interaction of diseases in a population, a condition known as a syndemic.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The term epidemiology is now widely applied to cover the description and causation of not only epidemic, infectious disease, but of disease in general, including related conditions and, especially since the 20th century, chronic diseases such as diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and cancer.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Some examples of topics examined through epidemiology include high blood pressure, mental illness and obesity.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Therefore, this epidemiology is based upon how the pattern of the disease causes change in the function of human beings.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The Greek physician Hippocrates, taught by Democritus, was known as the father of medicine, sought a logic to sickness; he is the first person known to have examined the relationships between the occurrence of disease and environmental influences.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Hippocrates believed sickness of the human body to be caused by an imbalance of the four humors (black bile, yellow bile, blood, and phlegm).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The cure to the sickness was to remove or add the humor in question to balance the body.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This belief led to the application of bloodletting and dieting in medicine.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] He coined the terms *endemic* (for diseases usually found in some places but not in others) and *epidemic* (for diseases that are seen at some times but not others).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In the middle of the 16th century, a doctor from Verona named Girolamo Fracastoro was the first to propose a theory that the very small, unseeable, particles that cause disease were alive.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] They were considered to be able to spread by air, multiply by themselves and to be destroyable by fire.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In this way he refuted Galen's miasma theory (poison gas in sick people).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In 1543 he wrote a book *De contagione et contagiosis morbis*, in which he was the first to promote personal and environmental hygiene to prevent disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The development of a sufficiently powerful microscope by Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1675 provided visual evidence of living particles consistent with a germ theory of disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] During the Ming dynasty, Wu Youke (1582–1652) developed the idea that some diseases were caused by transmissible agents, which he called *Li Qi* (戾气 or pestilential factors) when he observed various epidemics rage around him between 1641 and 1644.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] His book *Wen Yi Lun* (瘟疫论, Treatise on Pestilence/Treatise of Epidemic Diseases) can be regarded as the main etiological work that brought forward the concept.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] His concepts were still being considered in analysing SARS outbreak by WHO in 2004 in the context of traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Another pioneer, Thomas Sydenham (1624–1689), was the first to distinguish the fevers of Londoners in the later 1600s.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] His theories on cures of fevers met with much resistance from traditional physicians at the time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] He was not able to find the initial cause of the smallpox fever he researched and treated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] John Graunt, a haberdasher and amateur statistician, published *Natural and Political Observations ... upon the Bills of Mortality* in 1662.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In it, he analysed the mortality rolls in London before the Great Plague, presented one of the first life tables, and reported time trends for many diseases, new and old.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] He provided statistical evidence for many theories on disease, and also refuted some widespread ideas on them.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] John Snow is famous for his investigations into the causes of the 19th-century cholera epidemics, and is also known as the father of (modern) Epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] He began with noticing the significantly higher death rates in two areas supplied by Southwark Company.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] His identification of the Broad Street pump as the cause of the Soho epidemic is considered the classic example of epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Snow used chlorine in an attempt to clean the water and removed the handle; this ended the outbreak.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This has been perceived as a major event in the history of public health and regarded as the founding event of the science of epidemiology, having helped shape public health policies around the world.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, Snow's research and preventive measures to avoid further outbreaks were not fully accepted or put into practice until after his death due to the prevailing Miasma Theory of the time, a model of disease in which poor air quality was blamed for illness.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This was used to rationalize high rates of infection in impoverished areas instead of addressing the underlying issues of poor nutrition and sanitation, and was proven false by his work.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Other pioneers include Danish physician Peter Anton Schleisner, who in 1849 related his work on the prevention of the epidemic of neonatal tetanus on the Vestmanna Islands in Iceland.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Another important pioneer was Hungarian physician Ignaz Semmelweis, who in 1847 brought down infant mortality at a Vienna hospital by instituting a disinfection procedure.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] His findings were published in 1850, but his work was ill-received by his colleagues, who discontinued the procedure.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Disinfection did not become widely practiced until British surgeon Joseph Lister, aided by his colleague, chemist Thomas Anderson, was able to "discover" antiseptics in 1865 based on the earlier work of Louis Pasteur.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In the early 20th century, mathematical methods were introduced into epidemiology by Ronald Ross, Janet Lane-Claypon, Anderson Gray McKendrick, and others.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In 1927, William Ogilvy Kermack and Anderson Gray McKendrick published the foundational SIR (Susceptible-Infected-Recovered) model, applying mass-action kinetics from chemistry to disease transmission in populations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In a parallel development during the 1920s, German-Swiss pathologist Max Askanazy and others founded the International Society for Geographical Pathology to systematically investigate the geographical pathology of cancer and other non-infectious diseases across populations in different regions.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] After World War II, Richard Doll and other non-pathologists joined the field and advanced methods to study cancer, a disease with patterns and mode of occurrences that could not be suitably studied with the methods developed for epidemics of infectious diseases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Geography pathology eventually combined with infectious disease epidemiology to make the field that is epidemiology today.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Another breakthrough was the 1954 publication of the results of the British Doctors Study, led by Richard Doll and Austin Bradford Hill, which lent very strong statistical support to the link between tobacco smoking and lung cancer.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In the late 20th century, with the advancement of biomedical sciences, a number of molecular markers in blood, other biospecimens and environment were identified as predictors of development or risk of a certain disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiology research to examine the relationship between these biomarkers analyzed at the molecular level and disease was broadly named "molecular epidemiology".
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Specifically, "genetic epidemiology" has been used for epidemiology of germline genetic variation and disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Genetic variation is typically determined using DNA from peripheral blood leukocytes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Since the 2000s, genome-wide association studies (GWAS) have been commonly performed to identify genetic risk factors for many diseases and health conditions.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] While most molecular epidemiology studies are still using conventional disease diagnosis and classification systems, it is increasingly recognized that disease progression represents inherently heterogeneous processes differing from person to person.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Studies to examine the relationship between an exposure and molecular pathologic signature of disease (particularly cancer) became increasingly common throughout the 2000s.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, the use of molecular pathology in epidemiology posed unique challenges, including lack of research guidelines and standardized statistical methodologies, and paucity of interdisciplinary experts and training programs.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Furthermore, the concept of disease heterogeneity appears to conflict with the long-standing premise in epidemiology that individuals with the same disease name have similar etiologies and disease processes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In MPE, investigators analyze the relationships between (A) environmental, dietary, lifestyle and genetic factors; (B) alterations in cellular or extracellular molecules; and (C) evolution and progression of disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A better understanding of heterogeneity of disease pathogenesis will further contribute to elucidate etiologies of disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The MPE approach can be applied to not only neoplastic diseases but also non-neoplastic diseases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The concept and paradigm of MPE have become widespread in the 2010s.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] There is increasing recognition that a wide range of modern data sources, many not originating from healthcare or epidemiology, can be used for epidemiological study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Such digital epidemiology can include data from internet searching, mobile phone records and retail sales of drugs.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In observational studies, nature is allowed to "take its course", as epidemiologists observe from the sidelines.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Conversely, in experimental studies, the epidemiologist is the one in control of all of the factors entering a certain case study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiological studies are aimed, where possible, at revealing unbiased relationships between exposures such as alcohol or smoking, biological agents, stress, or chemicals to mortality or morbidity.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The identification of causal relationships between these exposures and outcomes is an important aspect of epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Modern epidemiologists use informatics and infodemiology as tools.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Observational studies have two components, descriptive and analytical.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Descriptive observations pertain to the "who, what, where and when of health-related state occurrence".
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, analytical observations deal more with the 'how' of a health-related event.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Experimental epidemiology contains three case types: randomized controlled trials (often used for a new medicine or drug testing), field trials (conducted on those at a high risk of contracting a disease), and community trials (research on social originating diseases).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The term 'epidemiologic triad' is used to describe the intersection of *Host*, *Agent*, and *Environment* in analyzing an outbreak.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Case-series may refer to the qualitative study of the experience of a single patient, or small group of patients with a similar diagnosis, or to a statistical factor with the potential to produce illness with periods when they are unexposed.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The former type of study is purely descriptive and cannot be used to make inferences about the general population of patients with that disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] These types of studies, in which an astute clinician identifies an unusual feature of a disease or a patient's history, may lead to a formulation of a new hypothesis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Using the data from the series, analytic studies could be done to investigate possible causal factors.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] These can include case-control studies or prospective studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A case-control study would involve matching comparable controls without the disease to the cases in the series.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A prospective study would involve following the case series over time to evaluate the disease's natural history.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The latter type, more formally described as self-controlled case-series studies, divide individual patient follow-up time into exposed and unexposed periods and use fixed-effects Poisson regression processes to compare the incidence rate of a given outcome between exposed and unexposed periods.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This technique has been extensively used in the study of adverse reactions to vaccination and has been shown in some circumstances to provide statistical power comparable to that available in cohort studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Case-control studies select subjects based on their disease status.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A group of individuals that are disease positive (the "case" group) is compared with a group of disease negative individuals (the "control" group).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The control group should ideally come from the same population that gave rise to the cases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The case-control study looks back through time at potential exposures that both groups (cases and controls) may have encountered.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A 2×2 table is constructed, displaying exposed cases (A), exposed controls (B), unexposed cases (C) and unexposed controls (D).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The statistic generated to measure association is the odds ratio (OR), which is the ratio of the odds of exposure in the cases (A/C) to the odds of exposure in the controls (B/D), i.e.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] If the OR is significantly greater than 1, then the conclusion is "those with the disease are more likely to have been exposed", whereas if it is close to 1 then the exposure and disease are not likely associated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] If the OR is far less than one, then this suggests that the exposure is a protective factor in the causation of the disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Case-control studies are usually faster and more cost-effective than cohort studies but are sensitive to bias (such as recall bias and selection bias).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The main challenge is to identify the appropriate control group; the distribution of exposure among the control group should be representative of the distribution in the population that gave rise to the cases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This can be achieved by drawing a random sample from the original population at risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This has as a consequence that the control group can contain people with the disease under study when the disease has a high attack rate in a population.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] where N is the ratio of cases to controls.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] As the odds ratio approaches 1, the number of cases required for statistical significance grows towards infinity; rendering case-control studies all but useless for low odds ratios.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Cohort studies select subjects based on their exposure status.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The study subjects should be at risk of the outcome under investigation at the beginning of the cohort study; this usually means that they should be disease free when the cohort study starts.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The cohort is followed through time to assess their later outcome status.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] An example of a cohort study would be the investigation of a cohort of smokers and non-smokers over time to estimate the incidence of lung cancer.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The same 2×2 table is constructed as with the case control study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, the point estimate generated is the relative risk (RR), which is the probability of disease for a person in the exposed group, *P*e = *A* / (*A* + *B*) over the probability of disease for a person in the unexposed group, *P**u* = *C* / (*C* + *D*), i.e.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Prospective studies have many benefits over case control studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The RR is a more powerful effect measure than the OR, as the OR is just an estimation of the RR, since true incidence cannot be calculated in a case control study where subjects are selected based on disease status.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Temporality can be established in a prospective study, and confounders are more easily controlled for.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, they are more costly, and there is a greater chance of losing subjects to follow-up based on the long time period over which the cohort is followed.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Cohort studies also are limited by the same equation for number of cases as for cohort studies, but, if the base incidence rate in the study population is very low, the number of cases required is reduced by 1⁄2.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Although epidemiology is sometimes viewed as a collection of statistical tools used to elucidate the associations of exposures to health outcomes, a deeper understanding of this science is that of discovering *causal* relationships.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] "Correlation does not imply causation" is a common theme for much of the epidemiological literature.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] For epidemiologists, the key is in the term inference.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Correlation, or at least association between two variables, is a necessary but not sufficient criterion for the inference that one variable causes the other.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiologists use gathered data and a broad range of biomedical and psychosocial theories in an iterative way to generate or expand theory, to test hypotheses, and to make educated, informed assertions about which relationships are causal, and about exactly how they are causal.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiologists emphasize that the "**one cause – one effect**" understanding is a simplistic mis-belief.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Most outcomes, whether disease or death, are caused by a chain or web consisting of many component causes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Causes can be distinguished as necessary, sufficient or probabilistic conditions.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] If a necessary condition can be identified and controlled (e.g., antibodies to a disease agent, energy in an injury), the harmful outcome can be avoided (Robertson, 2015).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] One tool regularly used to conceptualize the multicausality associated with disease is the causal pie model.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In 1965, Austin Bradford Hill proposed a series of considerations to help assess evidence of causation, which have come to be commonly known as the "Bradford Hill criteria".
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In contrast to the explicit intentions of their author, Hill's considerations are now sometimes taught as a checklist to be implemented for assessing causality.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Consistency of Data**: Consistent findings observed by different persons in different places with different samples strengthens the likelihood of an effect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Specificity**: Causation is likely if a very specific population at a specific site and disease with no other likely explanation.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The more specific an association between a factor and an effect is, the bigger the probability of a causal relationship.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Temporality**: The effect has to occur after the cause (and if there is an expected delay between the cause and expected effect, then the effect must occur after that delay).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Biological gradient**: Greater exposure should generally lead to greater incidence of the effect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, in some cases, the mere presence of the factor can trigger the effect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In other cases, an inverse proportion is observed: greater exposure leads to lower incidence.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Plausibility**: A plausible mechanism between cause and effect is helpful (but Hill noted that knowledge of the mechanism is limited by current knowledge).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Coherence**: Coherence between epidemiological and laboratory findings increases the likelihood of an effect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] However, Hill noted that "... lack of such [laboratory] evidence cannot nullify the epidemiological effect on associations".
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Experiment**: "Occasionally it is possible to appeal to experimental evidence".
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] **Analogy**: The effect of similar factors may be considered.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In United States law, epidemiology alone cannot prove that a causal association does not exist in general.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Conversely, it can be (and is in some circumstances) taken by US courts, in an individual case, to justify an inference that a causal association does exist, based upon a balance of probability.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The subdiscipline of forensic epidemiology is directed at the investigation of specific causation of disease or injury in individuals or groups of individuals in instances in which causation is disputed or is unclear, for presentation in legal settings.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiological practice and the results of epidemiological analysis make a significant contribution to emerging population-based health management frameworks.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Examples of organizations that use population-based health management that leverage the work and results of epidemiological practice include Canadian Strategy for Cancer Control, Health Canada Tobacco Control Programs, Rick Hansen Foundation, Canadian Tobacco Control Research Initiative.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Applied epidemiology is the practice of using epidemiological methods to protect or improve the health of a population.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] As the surveillance and reporting of diseases and other health factors become increasingly difficult in humanitarian crisis situations, the methodologies used to report the data are compromised.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] One study found that less than half (42.4%) of nutrition surveys sampled from humanitarian contexts correctly calculated the prevalence of malnutrition and only one-third (35.3%) of the surveys met the criteria for quality.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Among the mortality surveys, only 3.2% met the criteria for quality.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] As nutritional status and mortality rates help indicate the severity of a crisis, the tracking and reporting of these health factors is crucial.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Vital registries are usually the most effective ways to collect data, but in humanitarian contexts these registries can be non-existent, unreliable, or inaccessible.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] As such, mortality is often inaccurately measured using either prospective demographic surveillance or retrospective mortality surveys.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Prospective demographic surveillance requires much manpower and is difficult to implement in a spread-out population.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Retrospective mortality surveys are prone to selection and reporting biases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Other methods are being developed, but are not common practice yet.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The concept of waves in epidemics has implications especially for communicable diseases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A working definition for the term "epidemic wave" is based on two key features: 1) it comprises periods of upward or downward trends, and 2) these increases or decreases must be substantial and sustained over a period of time, in order to distinguish them from minor fluctuations or reporting errors.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The use of a consistent scientific definition is to provide a consistent language that can be used to communicate about and understand the progression of the COVID-19 pandemic, which would aid healthcare organizations and policymakers in resource planning and allocation.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Different fields in epidemiology have different levels of validity.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] One way to assess the validity of findings is the ratio of false-positives (claimed effects that are not correct) to false-negatives (studies which fail to support a true effect).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In genetic epidemiology, candidate-gene studies may produce over 100 false-positive findings for each false-negative.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] By contrast genome-wide association appear close to the reverse, with only one false positive for every 100 or more false-negatives.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This ratio has improved over time in genetic epidemiology, as the field has adopted stringent criteria.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] By contrast, other epidemiological fields have not required such rigorous reporting and are much less reliable as a result.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Random error is the result of fluctuations around a true value because of sampling variability.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] It can occur during data collection, coding, transfer, or analysis.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Examples of random errors include poorly worded questions, a misunderstanding in interpreting an individual answer from a particular respondent, or a typographical error during coding.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Random error affects measurement in a transient, inconsistent manner and it is impossible to correct for random error.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] There is a random error in all sampling procedures – sampling error.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Precision in epidemiological variables is a measure of random error.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Precision is also inversely related to random error, so that to reduce random error is to increase precision.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Confidence intervals are computed to demonstrate the precision of relative risk estimates.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The narrower the confidence interval, the more precise the relative risk estimate.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] There are two basic ways to reduce random error in an epidemiological study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The first is to increase the sample size of the study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In other words, add more subjects to your study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The second is to reduce the variability in measurement in the study.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] This might be accomplished by using a more precise measuring device or by increasing the number of measurements.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Note, that if sample size or number of measurements are increased, or a more precise measuring tool is purchased, the costs of the study are usually increased.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] There is usually an uneasy balance between the need for adequate precision and the practical issue of study cost.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A systematic error or bias occurs when there is a difference between the true value (in the population) and the observed value (in the study) from any cause other than sampling variability.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] An example of systematic error is if, unknown to you, the pulse oximeter you are using is set incorrectly and adds two points to the true value each time a measurement is taken.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The measuring device could be precise but not accurate.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Because the error happens in every instance, it is systematic.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Conclusions you draw based on that data will still be incorrect.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] But the error can be reproduced in the future (e.g., by using the same mis-set instrument).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A mistake in coding that affects *all* responses for that particular question is another example of a systematic error.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The validity of a study is dependent on the degree of systematic error.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Selection bias occurs when study subjects are selected or become part of the study as a result of a third, unmeasured variable which is associated with both the exposure and outcome of interest.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] For instance, it has repeatedly been noted that cigarette smokers and non smokers tend to differ in their study participation rates.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] (Sackett D cites the example of Seltzer et al., in which 85% of non smokers and 67% of smokers returned mailed questionnaires.) Such a difference in response will not lead to bias if it is not also associated with a systematic difference in outcome between the two response groups.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Information bias is bias arising from systematic error in the assessment of a variable.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In this example, recall bias probably occurred as a result of women who had had miscarriages having an apparent tendency to better recall and therefore report previous exposures.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Next to sample- and variable-related bias, bias can also arise from an imperfect study design.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] One example is immortal time bias, where during study period, there is some interval during which the outcome event cannot occur (making these individual "immortal").
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Confounding has traditionally been defined as bias arising from the co-occurrence or mixing of effects of extraneous factors, referred to as confounders, with the main effect(s) of interest.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] A more recent definition of confounding invokes the notion of *counterfactual* effects.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] According to this view, when one observes an outcome of interest, say Y=1 (as opposed to Y=0), in a given population A which is entirely exposed (i.e. exposure *X* = 1 for every unit of the population) the risk of this event will be *R*A1.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The counterfactual or unobserved risk *R*A0 corresponds to the risk which would have been observed if these same individuals had been unexposed (i.e.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] *X* = 0 for every unit of the population).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] The true effect of exposure therefore is: *R*A1 − *R*A0 (if one is interested in risk differences) or *R*A1/*R*A0 (if one is interested in relative risk).
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Since the counterfactual risk *R*A0 is unobservable we approximate it using a second population B and we actually measure the following relations: *R*A1 − *R*B0 or *R*A1/*R*B0.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In this situation, confounding occurs when *R*A0 ≠ *R*B0.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Some epidemiologists prefer to think of confounding separately from common categorizations of bias since, unlike selection and information bias, confounding stems from real causal effects.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Few universities have offered epidemiology as a course of study at the undergraduate level.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] An undergraduate program exists at Johns Hopkins University in which students who major in public health can take graduate-level courses—including epidemiology—during their senior year at the Bloomberg School of Public Health.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] In addition to its master's and doctoral degrees in epidemiology, the University of Michigan School of Public Health has offered undergraduate degree programs since 2017 that include coursework in epidemiology.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] As public health practitioners, epidemiologists work in a number of different settings.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Some epidemiologists work "in the field" (i.e., in the community; commonly in a public health service), and are often at the forefront of investigating and combating disease outbreaks.
[src:epidemiology-methods/epidemiology] Epidemiologists can also work in for-profit organizations (e.g., pharmaceutical and medical device companies) in groups such as market research or clinical development.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] In epidemiology, **incidence** reflects the number of new cases of a given medical condition in a population within a specified period of time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] For example, if a population contains 1,000 persons and 28 develop a condition from the time the disease first occurred until two years later, the cumulative incidence is 28 cases per 1,000 persons, i.e.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] One of the important advantages of incidence rate is that it doesn't require all subjects to be present for the whole study because it's only interested in the time at risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Incidence should not be confused with prevalence, which is the proportion of cases in the population at a given time rather than rate of occurrence of new cases.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Thus, incidence conveys information about the risk of contracting the disease, whereas prevalence indicates how widespread the disease is.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Prevalence is the proportion of the total number of cases to the total population and is more a measure of the burden of the disease on society with no regard to time at risk or when subjects may have been exposed to a possible risk factor.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Prevalence can also be measured with respect to a specific subgroup of a population.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Incidence is usually more useful than prevalence in understanding the disease etiology: for example, if the incidence rate of a disease in a population increases, then there is a risk factor that promotes the incidence.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] For example, consider a disease that takes a long time to cure and was widespread in 2002 but dissipated in 2003.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] This disease will have both high incidence and high prevalence in 2002, but in 2003 it will have a low incidence yet will continue to have a high prevalence (because it takes a long time to cure, so the fraction of individuals that are affected remains high).
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] In contrast, a disease that has a short duration may have a low prevalence and a high incidence.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] When the incidence is approximately constant for the duration of the disease, prevalence is approximately the product of disease incidence and average disease duration, so *prevalence = incidence × duration*.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] The importance of this equation is in the relation between prevalence and incidence; for example, when the incidence increases, then the prevalence must also increase.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Note that this relation does not hold for age-specific prevalence and incidence, where the relation becomes more complicated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] If you were to measure prevalence you would simply take the total number of cases (25 + 20 + 30 = 75) and divide by your sample population (225).
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] So prevalence would be 75/225 = 0.33 or 33% (by the end of the study).
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] This tells you how widespread HIV is in your sample population, but little about the actual risk of developing HIV for any person over a coming year.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] To measure incidence rate you must take into account how many years each person contributed to the study, and when they developed HIV because when a subject develops HIV he stops being at risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] When it is not known exactly when a person develops the disease in question, epidemiologists frequently use the actuarial method, and assume it was developed at a half-way point between follow-ups.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] Now take the 50 new cases of HIV, and divide by 1775 to get 0.028, or 28 cases of HIV per 1000 population, per year.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] In other words, if you were to follow 1000 people for one year, you would see 28 new cases of HIV.
[src:epidemiology-methods/incidence-epidemiology] This is a much more accurate measure of risk than prevalence.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] In epidemiology, **prevalence** is the proportion of a particular population found to be affected by a medical condition (typically a disease or a risk factor such as smoking or seatbelt use) at a specific time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] It is derived by comparing the number of people found to have the condition with the total number of people studied and is usually expressed as a fraction, a percentage, or the number of cases per 10,000 or 100,000 people.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Prevalence is most often used in questionnaire studies.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Prevalence is the number of disease cases *present*in a particular population at a given time, whereas incidence is the number of new cases that *develop*during a specified time period.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Prevalence answers "How many people have this disease right now?" or "How many people have had this disease during this time period?".
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Incidence answers "How many people acquired the disease [during a specified time period]?".
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] However, mathematically, prevalence is proportional to the product of the incidence and the average duration of the disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Caution must be practiced as this relationship is only applicable when the following two conditions are met: 1) prevalence is low and 2) the duration is constant (or an average can be taken).
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] A general formulation requires differential equations.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] In science, *prevalence* describes a proportion (typically expressed as a percentage).
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] For example, the prevalence of obesity among American adults in 2001 was estimated by the U.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Centers for Disease Control (CDC) at approximately 20.9%.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Prevalence is a term that means being widespread and it is distinct from incidence.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Prevalence is a measurement of *all* individuals affected by the disease at a particular time, whereas incidence is a measurement of the number of *new* individuals who contract a disease during a particular period of time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Prevalence is a useful parameter when talking about long-lasting diseases, such as HIV, but incidence is more useful when talking about diseases of short duration, such as chickenpox.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] The relationship between incidence (rate), point prevalence (ratio) and period prevalence (ratio) is easily explained via an analogy with photography.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Point prevalence is akin to a flashlit photograph: what is happening at this instant frozen in time.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Period prevalence is analogous to a long exposure (seconds, rather than an instant) photograph: the number of events recorded in the photo whilst the camera shutter was open.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] In a movie each frame records an instant (point prevalence); by looking from frame to frame one notices new events (incident events) and can relate the number of such events to a period (number of frames); see incidence rate.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] Hence, a very high percentage of subjects who seem to have a history of a disorder at interview are false positives for such a medical condition and apparently never developed a fully clinical syndrome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] A different but related problem in evaluating the public health significance of psychiatric conditions has been highlighted by Robert Spitzer of Columbia University: fulfillment of diagnostic criteria and the resulting diagnosis do not necessarily imply need for treatment.
[src:epidemiology-methods/prevalence] A well-known statistical problem arises when ascertaining rates for disorders and conditions with a relatively low population prevalence or base rate.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] The **relative risk (RR)** or **risk ratio** is the ratio of the probability of an outcome in an exposed group to the probability of an outcome in an unexposed group.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Together with risk difference and odds ratio, relative risk measures the association between the exposure and the outcome.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Relative risk is mostly used in the statistical analysis of the data of ecological, cohort, medical and intervention studies, to estimate the strength of the association between exposures (treatments or risk factors) and outcomes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Mathematically, it is the incidence rate of the outcome in the exposed group, $I_{e}$ , divided by the rate of the unexposed group, $I_{u}$ .
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] As such, it is used to compare the risk of an adverse outcome when receiving a medical treatment versus no treatment (or placebo), or for environmental risk factors.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] In this case, apixaban is a protective factor rather than a risk factor, because it reduces the risk of disease.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] As always, correlation does not mean causation; the causation could be reversed, or they could both be caused by a common confounding variable.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] The relative risk of having cancer when in the hospital versus at home, for example, would be greater than 1, but that is because having cancer causes people to go to the hospital.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Relative risk is commonly used to present the results of randomized controlled trials.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] This can be problematic if the relative risk is presented without the absolute measures, such as absolute risk, or risk difference.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] In cases where the base rate of the outcome is low, large or small values of relative risk may not translate to significant effects, and the importance of the effects to the public health can be overestimated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Equivalently, in cases where the base rate of the outcome is high, values of the relative risk close to 1 may still result in a significant effect, and their effects can be underestimated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Thus, presentation of both absolute and relative measures is recommended.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] where $z_{\alpha }$ is the standard score for the chosen level of significance.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] To find the confidence interval around the RR itself, the two bounds of the above confidence interval can be exponentiated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] In regression models, the exposure is typically included as an indicator variable along with other factors that may affect risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] The relative risk is usually reported as calculated for the mean of the sample values of the explanatory variables.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] The relative risk is different from the odds ratio, although the odds ratio asymptotically approaches the relative risk for small probabilities of outcomes.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] If IE is substantially smaller than *IN*, then IE/(IE + IN) $\scriptstyle \approx$ IE/IN.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Similarly, if CE is much smaller than CN, then CE/(CN + CE) $\scriptstyle \approx$ CE/CN.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] In practice the odds ratio is commonly used for case-control studies, as the relative risk cannot be estimated.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] In fact, the odds ratio has much more common use in statistics, since logistic regression, often associated with clinical trials, works with the log of the odds ratio, not relative risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Since relative risk is a more intuitive measure of effectiveness, the distinction is important especially in cases of medium to high probabilities.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] If action A carries a risk of 99.9% and action B a risk of 99.0% then the relative risk is just over 1, while the odds associated with action A are more than 10 times higher than the odds with B.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] In statistical modelling, approaches like Poisson regression (for counts of events per unit exposure) have relative risk interpretations: the estimated effect of an explanatory variable is multiplicative on the rate and thus leads to a relative risk.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] Logistic regression (for binary outcomes, or counts of successes out of a number of trials) must be interpreted in odds-ratio terms: the effect of an explanatory variable is multiplicative on the odds and thus leads to an odds ratio.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] We could assume a disease noted by D , and no disease noted by $\neg D$ , exposure noted by E , and no exposure noted by $\neg E$ .
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] This way the relative risk can be interpreted in Bayesian terms as the posterior ratio of the exposure (i.e. after seeing the disease) normalized by the prior ratio of exposure.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] If the posterior ratio of exposure is similar to that of the prior, the effect is approximately 1, indicating no association with the disease, since it didn't change beliefs of the exposure.
[src:epidemiology-methods/relative-risk] If on the other hand, the posterior ratio of exposure is smaller or higher than that of the prior ratio, then the disease has changed the view of the exposure danger, and the magnitude of this change is the relative risk.
